1
00:00:12,800 --> 00:00:16,800
www.subtitles.hr

2
00:00:19,800 --> 00:00:24,294
Christ is risen from the dead,
trampling down death by death.

3
00:00:24,371 --> 00:00:27,807
And upon those in the tomb.

4
00:00:27,874 --> 00:00:31,366
Bestowing life.

5
00:01:46,319 --> 00:01:51,916
When I will come to see you.

6
00:01:51,992 --> 00:01:57,157
Rapid flow the dear rivers

7
00:01:57,230 --> 00:02:02,691
I want you to carry away
all my sorrow.

8
00:02:02,769 --> 00:02:08,207
With your fast waters.

9
00:02:08,942 --> 00:02:11,274
On the fields
the girls were strolling.

10
00:02:11,344 --> 00:02:16,111
Singing and picking up
corn flowers.

11
00:02:16,183 --> 00:02:18,617
There they met the young fellow.

12
00:02:18,685 --> 00:02:21,210
He gave them a look
as though he were superior.

13
00:02:21,288 --> 00:02:25,054
Scarcely looked at them.

14
00:02:25,292 --> 00:02:28,455
Scarcely looked at them.

15
00:02:30,730 --> 00:02:32,493
Katusha!

16
00:02:32,732 --> 00:02:35,360
Katusha!

17
00:02:42,642 --> 00:02:44,405
What are you doing
in the fields again?

18
00:02:44,478 --> 00:02:46,343
There was nothing more
to do in the house,

19
00:02:46,413 --> 00:02:48,176
so I came here to help!

20
00:02:48,248 --> 00:02:52,275
You'll catch it when they
find out you're in the fields again!

21
00:02:52,352 --> 00:02:55,719
And what are you thinking of?
Don't you know he's arriving today?

22
00:02:55,789 --> 00:02:58,349
He? Who?

23
00:02:58,425 --> 00:03:01,087
Who? You numbskull!

24
00:03:01,161 --> 00:03:03,789
The prince! Dmitri Ivanovitch!

25
00:03:03,864 --> 00:03:06,264
He's on his way
from the station now!

26
00:03:10,537 --> 00:03:12,164
I thought it was tomorrow!

27
00:03:12,239 --> 00:03:15,072
Tomorrow! Go into the house
and put on your Sunday frock!

28
00:03:15,141 --> 00:03:17,507
You dirty girl!
And comb your hair!

29
00:03:17,577 --> 00:03:18,601
I will!

30
00:03:18,678 --> 00:03:20,703
And don't forget
his welcoming gift!

31
00:03:20,780 --> 00:03:22,111
Have you?

32
00:03:30,957 --> 00:03:34,188
What are you smelling, Dmitri?
I don't smell anything.

33
00:03:34,261 --> 00:03:37,355
Spring. You don't smell the spring?

34
00:03:37,430 --> 00:03:38,624
Oh, that!

35
00:03:38,698 --> 00:03:41,258
This air. It's wonderful.

36
00:03:41,334 --> 00:03:42,678
It's going to be
a wonderful summer.

37
00:03:42,702 --> 00:03:45,227
But there'll be
no loafing for you, Dmitri.

38
00:03:45,305 --> 00:03:46,966
You'll spend the summer in study.

39
00:03:47,040 --> 00:03:50,373
We shall be very disappointed if you
fail to pass your officer's examination.

40
00:03:50,443 --> 00:03:52,934
Aunt Marie,
I don't like the army.

41
00:03:53,013 --> 00:03:55,004
- What?
- I don't like what it represents.

42
00:03:55,081 --> 00:03:57,481
I don't see why I should be
an officer, anyway.

43
00:03:57,551 --> 00:04:00,213
Because your father was one,
and your grandfather!

44
00:04:00,287 --> 00:04:03,120
Because the Nekhlyudovs
have always served their czar.

45
00:04:03,189 --> 00:04:05,419
I don't know whether
I want to serve my czar.

46
00:04:05,492 --> 00:04:06,857
- Dmitri, dear boy!
- What is this?

47
00:04:06,927 --> 00:04:08,224
I want to serve my country.

48
00:04:08,295 --> 00:04:10,320
That's why I'd rather go
into civil service.

49
00:04:10,397 --> 00:04:12,228
Russia's in a pretty rotten condition.

50
00:04:12,299 --> 00:04:13,299
- Dmitri!
- Dmitri!

51
00:04:13,366 --> 00:04:15,630
We're going to have
a revolution if we don't look out.

52
00:04:15,702 --> 00:04:17,897
Revolution in Russia? Ridiculous.

53
00:04:17,971 --> 00:04:19,495
You think so?
Well, let me tell you.

54
00:04:19,573 --> 00:04:22,337
When our rulers place yokes
around our necks...

55
00:04:22,409 --> 00:04:25,401
When tyrants
grind their heels in our faces...

56
00:04:25,478 --> 00:04:27,810
When oppression rules
instead of justice...

57
00:04:27,881 --> 00:04:30,679
Where did you
pick up this nonsense?

58
00:04:31,651 --> 00:04:33,141
I read it in a book.

59
00:04:46,733 --> 00:04:48,257
Good morning. Good morning.

60
00:04:48,335 --> 00:04:50,735
The prince must be
a big man now!

61
00:04:50,804 --> 00:04:52,704
Oh, yes. Don't move all around.

62
00:04:52,772 --> 00:04:54,171
Stand in one place.

63
00:04:54,240 --> 00:04:56,003
Over this way.

64
00:04:56,443 --> 00:04:59,071
- Ivan, you stand there.
- Yes, Anton Ivanovitch.

65
00:04:59,145 --> 00:05:02,376
Here, you stand in line.
You get over there.

66
00:05:24,437 --> 00:05:27,497
Welcome, Your Highness,
Dmitri Ivanovitch!

67
00:05:37,183 --> 00:05:38,411
Come around.

68
00:05:38,485 --> 00:05:41,079
Everyone, just as I told you.

69
00:05:41,154 --> 00:05:43,588
Now one at a time.

70
00:05:43,657 --> 00:05:44,749
Ivan.

71
00:05:49,696 --> 00:05:53,757
- Welcome, Your Highness.
- Thank you. Thank you very much.

72
00:05:53,833 --> 00:05:57,860
Oh. Thank you.
Thank you very much.

73
00:05:57,937 --> 00:05:58,961
Thank you.

74
00:05:59,039 --> 00:06:01,473
- May God bless Your Highness.
- Oh, thank you.

75
00:06:01,541 --> 00:06:04,874
Thank you very much. Thank you.

76
00:06:04,944 --> 00:06:07,208
Why do they give me food?
They need it, and we don't.

77
00:06:07,280 --> 00:06:08,591
Hush! It's a custom...
It's always done!

78
00:06:08,615 --> 00:06:10,947
Thank you very much.
But really, I don't like taking it.

79
00:06:11,017 --> 00:06:13,485
Anton, His Highness
is tired after his journey.

80
00:06:13,553 --> 00:06:14,997
Tell them to place
their gifts on the steps

81
00:06:15,021 --> 00:06:16,381
and give them
His Highness' thanks.

82
00:06:16,423 --> 00:06:19,449
But, Aunt Marie, I'm not tired,
and I should thank them personally.

83
00:06:19,526 --> 00:06:21,187
Friends!

84
00:06:22,095 --> 00:06:24,563
Dear friends!
And brothers in suffering!

85
00:06:24,631 --> 00:06:25,928
That'll do, Dmitri. Come.

86
00:06:25,999 --> 00:06:28,524
- Tell them, Anton.
- But, Aunt Marie...

87
00:06:36,176 --> 00:06:38,371
Brothers in suffering, indeed!

88
00:06:38,445 --> 00:06:39,673
Really, Dmitri!

89
00:06:44,217 --> 00:06:46,082
Welcome, Dmitri Ivanovitch.

90
00:06:46,152 --> 00:06:47,779
I wish you every happiness...

91
00:06:47,854 --> 00:06:49,981
and... and happiness!

92
00:06:50,056 --> 00:06:52,047
And I give you this for good luck!

93
00:06:53,226 --> 00:06:55,023
Katusha?

94
00:06:55,095 --> 00:06:58,496
No! Oh, my goodness, it is.

95
00:06:58,565 --> 00:06:59,896
Why, of all the...

96
00:06:59,966 --> 00:07:01,844
This is the most
startling thing I've ever seen!

97
00:07:01,868 --> 00:07:03,068
I mean the way you've changed!

98
00:07:03,103 --> 00:07:05,264
Why, six years ago...
I can't believe my eyes...

99
00:07:05,338 --> 00:07:07,499
You were just a little girl
with freckles, wasn't she?

100
00:07:07,574 --> 00:07:09,132
She has grown up.

101
00:07:09,209 --> 00:07:11,200
You were just
a little freckled cocoon.

102
00:07:11,277 --> 00:07:13,837
And now,
now you are a butterfly!

103
00:07:13,913 --> 00:07:16,279
A beautiful
white and golden butterfly!

104
00:07:16,349 --> 00:07:18,510
If our butterfly could manage it,

105
00:07:18,585 --> 00:07:21,452
I wish she would serve us tea
in the sitting room.

106
00:07:22,122 --> 00:07:23,885
You'll want to wash first, Dmitri.

107
00:07:23,957 --> 00:07:25,925
You'll find your old room
upstairs ready for you.

108
00:07:25,992 --> 00:07:27,960
I can't get over it!
She's become a raving beauty!

109
00:07:28,027 --> 00:07:29,289
She's a very sweet girl.

110
00:07:29,362 --> 00:07:31,227
She's a servant.
You're not forgetting that.

111
00:07:31,297 --> 00:07:33,843
- What difference does that make?
- She's not to be treated as an equal.

112
00:07:33,867 --> 00:07:35,698
Why not?
We practically grew up together.

113
00:07:35,769 --> 00:07:37,168
Well, now, you are grown up.

114
00:07:37,237 --> 00:07:39,432
You're not of the same class
and never can be.

115
00:07:39,506 --> 00:07:41,872
Even though your Aunt Sophie
is teaching her French

116
00:07:41,941 --> 00:07:43,340
and trying to make a lady of her.

117
00:07:43,409 --> 00:07:45,240
Why, Marie,
I'm doing nothing of the kind.

118
00:07:45,311 --> 00:07:46,471
I'm very fond of the child,

119
00:07:46,546 --> 00:07:48,124
and she has
a natural aptitude for learning.

120
00:07:48,148 --> 00:07:49,658
You will never make
a peasant into a lady.

121
00:07:49,682 --> 00:07:50,876
I'm not so sure of that.

122
00:07:50,950 --> 00:07:53,195
After all, what's the difference
between peasants and ourselves?

123
00:07:53,219 --> 00:07:54,948
Suppose we all took our clothes off...

124
00:07:55,021 --> 00:07:56,511
What?

125
00:07:57,791 --> 00:08:00,589
Well, I don't mean
that we really should...

126
00:08:00,660 --> 00:08:02,992
What I mean is,
figuratively speaking.

127
00:08:03,062 --> 00:08:04,154
If...

128
00:08:04,664 --> 00:08:07,030
Is there warm water in my room?

129
00:08:07,100 --> 00:08:08,362
Yes.

130
00:08:20,947 --> 00:08:22,437
Katusha!

131
00:08:24,083 --> 00:08:27,450
- Where are you?
- With the cow!

132
00:08:32,458 --> 00:08:33,584
What a book!

133
00:08:33,660 --> 00:08:35,787
What marvelous thoughts
this writer has!

134
00:08:35,862 --> 00:08:38,387
- You've got to read it.
- What is it called?

135
00:08:38,464 --> 00:08:39,658
Look.

136
00:08:39,732 --> 00:08:43,293
<i>"Land and Freedom. "</i>

137
00:08:43,403 --> 00:08:44,734
The government
has suppressed it.

138
00:08:44,804 --> 00:08:47,432
I've met Simonson, the author.
He's a great thinker.

139
00:08:47,507 --> 00:08:49,065
The police are after him.

140
00:08:49,142 --> 00:08:50,734
Is it an immoral book?

141
00:08:50,810 --> 00:08:52,437
It's the most moral book
ever written.

142
00:08:52,512 --> 00:08:54,104
It says that all people are equal

143
00:08:54,180 --> 00:08:55,791
and that the land
should belong to everybody.

144
00:08:55,815 --> 00:08:57,593
- Is there a love story?
- No, no, of course not.

145
00:08:57,617 --> 00:08:59,676
- Love stories are for children.
- I like them.

146
00:08:59,752 --> 00:09:02,380
They're all right in their place,
but before love comes humanity.

147
00:09:02,455 --> 00:09:03,615
People.

148
00:09:03,690 --> 00:09:05,453
But if people didn't fall in love,

149
00:09:05,525 --> 00:09:07,652
there wouldn't be any people.

150
00:09:07,727 --> 00:09:12,221
Well, yes, but... but you do believe,
of course, that we're all equal?

151
00:09:12,298 --> 00:09:15,131
- Are we?
- Not yet, but we should be.

152
00:09:16,536 --> 00:09:19,061
Then who would be servant
and who would be master?

153
00:09:19,138 --> 00:09:21,572
There wouldn't be any servants.
We'd all be masters.

154
00:09:21,641 --> 00:09:22,938
Who would do the work then?

155
00:09:23,009 --> 00:09:24,340
Oh, you numbskull.

156
00:09:24,410 --> 00:09:27,174
Katusha, you're only beautiful.
You're not bright.

157
00:09:27,247 --> 00:09:28,908
Now look here. Stop that!

158
00:09:28,982 --> 00:09:31,849
Who does the air belong to?

159
00:09:33,653 --> 00:09:34,847
I don't know.

160
00:09:34,921 --> 00:09:36,855
Do you have to pay
to breathe air?

161
00:09:36,923 --> 00:09:38,220
No.

162
00:09:38,291 --> 00:09:39,758
Now we are getting somewhere.

163
00:09:39,826 --> 00:09:41,657
And the water,
who owns the water?

164
00:09:41,728 --> 00:09:44,595
- What kind of water?
- There's only one kind of water!

165
00:09:44,664 --> 00:09:45,858
Who owns it?

166
00:09:46,933 --> 00:09:48,400
The man who owns the well?

167
00:09:48,468 --> 00:09:52,234
No, no... the water in the ocean.
Salt water, let's say.

168
00:09:52,305 --> 00:09:55,069
What is it good for,
except pickles?

169
00:09:55,141 --> 00:09:56,733
You're hopeless.

170
00:09:56,809 --> 00:09:59,300
But I'll make you
understand this if I have to...

171
00:09:59,379 --> 00:10:01,472
Get up.

172
00:10:02,081 --> 00:10:03,105
Come here.

173
00:10:05,852 --> 00:10:09,811
Now kiss me.

174
00:10:09,889 --> 00:10:11,686
Come on, I'm ordering you to.

175
00:10:11,758 --> 00:10:13,191
Kiss me.

176
00:10:15,461 --> 00:10:17,622
There! Now do you see
what I mean?

177
00:10:17,697 --> 00:10:18,789
No.

178
00:10:18,865 --> 00:10:21,595
- Why did you kiss me?
- Because you asked me to.

179
00:10:21,668 --> 00:10:24,034
- Why did I ask you to?
- I don't know.

180
00:10:24,103 --> 00:10:25,161
Well, I'll tell you why.

181
00:10:25,238 --> 00:10:28,139
Because being a nobleman, I knew
that if I asked you to do something,

182
00:10:28,207 --> 00:10:29,231
you'd have to do it.

183
00:10:29,309 --> 00:10:31,675
Now why have I the right
to force you against your will?

184
00:10:31,744 --> 00:10:32,904
Why should...

185
00:10:32,979 --> 00:10:36,972
- Well, you didn't exactly force me.
- Keep quiet when I'm talking.

186
00:10:37,050 --> 00:10:38,711
Who is it
that gives me that privilege?

187
00:10:38,785 --> 00:10:41,583
God? No, no, no...
the accident of birth.

188
00:10:41,654 --> 00:10:43,121
Why should that be the...

189
00:10:43,957 --> 00:10:46,391
What's the matter?

190
00:10:46,459 --> 00:10:50,361
First, you ask me to kiss you,
and then when I do what you ask,

191
00:10:50,430 --> 00:10:51,829
you shout at me.

192
00:10:51,898 --> 00:10:54,628
No, no, Katusha, don't cry.
Don't cry. I was only arguing.

193
00:10:54,701 --> 00:10:56,712
I was just trying to show you
how unequal things are.

194
00:10:56,736 --> 00:10:58,966
It was just
a philosophical discussion.

195
00:10:59,038 --> 00:11:01,131
But you asked me to...

196
00:11:01,207 --> 00:11:03,167
I know, but I was
just trying to put over a point.

197
00:11:03,209 --> 00:11:05,370
That's all. I didn't have
any desire to kiss you.

198
00:11:05,445 --> 00:11:08,642
No, no, nothing like that.
It was all pure reasoning.

199
00:11:08,715 --> 00:11:11,775
I was just illustrating
an unjust social condition.

200
00:11:11,851 --> 00:11:14,411
There, there. That's all it was.

201
00:11:14,487 --> 00:11:15,977
Don't cry, Katusha.

202
00:11:19,559 --> 00:11:21,390
They've been together
all the summer,

203
00:11:21,461 --> 00:11:22,985
every opportunity they could get.

204
00:11:23,062 --> 00:11:24,825
I don't think
there's any harm in it, Marie.

205
00:11:24,897 --> 00:11:27,417
Every time I've seen them together,
they've been reading a book.

206
00:11:27,467 --> 00:11:30,800
A book can always be put aside.
I'm glad he's leaving today.

207
00:11:39,946 --> 00:11:43,313
Where are you going with it?
Oh, be reasonable, Katusha.

208
00:11:43,383 --> 00:11:44,782
I can't let you have my hat.

209
00:11:44,851 --> 00:11:47,445
The school will have my hide
if I came back without it.

210
00:11:47,520 --> 00:11:49,681
It's part of my uniform.

211
00:11:50,723 --> 00:11:55,183
- Come and get it!
- Please, Katusha! Please!

212
00:12:09,942 --> 00:12:11,068
Here.

213
00:12:12,412 --> 00:12:14,437
Now when you are gone,

214
00:12:14,514 --> 00:12:16,379
I'll have nothing
to remember you by.

215
00:12:16,449 --> 00:12:19,350
If I don't leave you something,
you'll forget me?

216
00:12:20,953 --> 00:12:22,978
No, Dmitri Ivanovitch.

217
00:12:23,990 --> 00:12:26,083
I'll never forget you.

218
00:12:29,762 --> 00:12:31,923
It's been
a marvelous summer, hasn't it?

219
00:12:33,166 --> 00:12:34,793
Next summer, when I come back,

220
00:12:34,867 --> 00:12:36,425
that'll be a marvelous one, too.

221
00:12:36,502 --> 00:12:38,697
Every summer after that.

222
00:12:38,771 --> 00:12:42,639
Ten months
before I'll see you again.

223
00:12:42,708 --> 00:12:46,769
- It's going to be hard to wait.
- For me, too.

224
00:12:46,846 --> 00:12:49,872
Well, then, let's think
only of four years from now.

225
00:12:49,949 --> 00:12:54,181
After I quit the army,
then we can be together all the time.

226
00:12:56,756 --> 00:12:58,485
There.

227
00:12:58,558 --> 00:13:03,621
You can remember me,
at least until these fade.

228
00:13:03,696 --> 00:13:06,631
And forever after.

229
00:13:09,602 --> 00:13:12,628
Where did you get violets
as late as this?

230
00:13:12,705 --> 00:13:15,139
In the conservatory.

231
00:13:16,709 --> 00:13:19,200
If your aunts
knew I took them...

232
00:13:20,713 --> 00:13:23,477
They'd be angry, wouldn't they?

233
00:13:23,549 --> 00:13:24,777
Yes.

234
00:13:25,918 --> 00:13:27,749
They would be angry.

235
00:13:35,962 --> 00:13:38,897
You will try and pass your
examinations, Dmitri, dear, won't you?

236
00:13:38,965 --> 00:13:39,965
I will, Aunt Sophie.

237
00:13:40,032 --> 00:13:41,443
You'll like army life.
Men always do.

238
00:13:41,467 --> 00:13:43,128
Thank you, Aunt Marie.
It's been lovely.

239
00:13:43,202 --> 00:13:44,847
You be a good boy,
and don't drink too much.

240
00:13:44,871 --> 00:13:46,395
Yes, Aunt Sophie, I will.

241
00:13:46,472 --> 00:13:47,549
- Good-bye, dear.
- Good-bye.

242
00:13:47,573 --> 00:13:48,972
Good-bye. Good-bye.

243
00:13:49,041 --> 00:13:51,737
- Good-bye!
- Good-bye!

244
00:13:51,811 --> 00:13:53,779
Good-bye!

245
00:13:53,846 --> 00:13:57,942
- Good-bye!
- Good-bye, dear. Good-bye!

246
00:14:09,428 --> 00:14:11,293
- Yes, sir.
- Oh, relax.

247
00:14:11,364 --> 00:14:12,854
I haven't come here officially.

248
00:14:12,932 --> 00:14:16,163
I'm here because you've been making
a great fool of yourself, Lieutenant.

249
00:14:16,235 --> 00:14:19,602
You were very rude
to General Davidoff's wife last night.

250
00:14:19,672 --> 00:14:21,503
- Rude? I, sir?
